      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Unstructured State Management\nUnstructured state uses a dictionary-like approach, offering flexibility and simplicity \nfor straightforward applications.\n​\nHow It Works\nWith unstructured state:\nYou access state via self.state which behaves like a dictionary\nYou can freely add, modify, or remove keys at any point\nAll state is automatically available to all flow methods",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Unstructured State Management\nUnstructured state uses a dictionary-like approach, offering flexibility and simplicity \nfor straightforward applications.\n​\nHow It Works\nWith unstructured state:\nYou access state via self.state which behaves like a dictionary\nYou can freely add, modify, or remove keys at any point\nAll state is automatically available to all flow methods",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.35
    },
    {
      "id": "gaSa00EfQyjBjoiPyw8tF",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 248.51559448242188,
      "y": 1654.0233825047828,
      "width": 596.75927734375,
      "height": 243,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "a9",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1089817026,
      "version": 59,
      "versionNonce": 1769611919,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1773504096333,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "\nWhen to Use Unstructured State\nUnstructured state is ideal for:\nQuick prototyping and simple flows\nDynamically evolving state needs\nCases where the structure may not be known in advance\nFlows with simple state requirements\nWhile flexible, unstructured state lacks type checking and schema\n validation, which can lead to errors in complex applications.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "\nWhen to Use Unstructured State\nUnstructured state is ideal for:\nQuick prototyping and simple flows\nDynamically evolving state needs\nCases where the structure may not be known in advance\nFlows with simple state requirements\nWhile flexible, unstructured state lacks type checking and schema\n validation, which can lead to errors in complex applications.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.35
    },
    {
      "id": "dDL-R-77zKwdisTTyywat",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 249.0104217529297,
      "y": 1947.6821954515265,
      "width": 707.4390258789062,
      "height": 297,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "aB",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1092144862,
      "version": 142,
      "versionNonce": 2065580975,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1773504077569,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Structured State Management\nStructured state uses Pydantic models to define a schema for your flow’s state\n, providing type safety, validation, and better developer experience.\n​\nHow It Works\nWith structured state:\nYou define a Pydantic model that represents your state structure\nYou pass this model type to your Flow class as a type parameter\nYou access state via self.state, which behaves like a Pydantic model instance\nAll fields are validated according to their defined types\nYou get IDE autocompletion and type checking support",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Structured State Management\nStructured state uses Pydantic models to define a schema for your flow’s state\n, providing type safety, validation, and better developer experience.\n​\nHow It Works\nWith structured state:\nYou define a Pydantic model that represents your state structure\nYou pass this model type to your Flow class as a type parameter\nYou access state via self.state, which behaves like a Pydantic model instance\nAll fields are validated according to their defined types\nYou get IDE autocompletion and type checking support",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.35
    },
    {
      "id": "CWrZZA8gQxQMjb_suLoUf",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 247.65625,
      "y": 2278.1509871482867,
      "width": 721.8590698242188,
      "height": 459,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "aC",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 528340126,
      "version": 230,
      "versionNonce": 451137935,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1773504082502,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "\nBenefits of Structured State\n\nUsing structured state provides several advantages:\nType Safety - Catch type errors at development time\nSelf-Documentation - The state model clearly documents what data is available\nValidation - Automatic validation of data types and constraints\nIDE Support - Get autocomplete and inline documentation\nDefault Values - Easily define fallbacks for missing data\n​\nWhen to Use Structured State\n\nStructured state is recommended for:\nComplex flows with well-defined data schemas\nTeam projects where multiple developers work on the same code\nApplications where data validation is important\nFlows that need to enforce specific data types and constraints",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "\nBenefits of Structured State\n\nUsing structured state provides several advantages:\nType Safety - Catch type errors at development time\nSelf-Documentation - The state model clearly documents what data is available\nValidation - Automatic validation of data types and constraints\nIDE Support - Get autocomplete and inline documentation\nDefault Values - Easily define fallbacks for missing data\n​\nWhen to Use Structured State\n\nStructured state is recommended for:\nComplex flows with well-defined data schemas\nTeam projects where multiple developers work on the same code\nApplications where data validation is important\nFlows that need to enforce specific data types and constraints",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.35
    },
